    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1455621200" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1455621200" />
    <a title="Pixie Dust" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/15371641-pixie-dust"><img alt="Pixie Dust" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1455621200?book_show_action=true">Nov 29, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Pixie Dust" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Pixie Dust" href="/user/show/15371641-pixie-dust">Pixie Dust</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1455621200" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14653776227400839837">This was one of my favourite childhood books. Rereading it now for the first time as an adult, I am convinced this is one of those evergreen stories that will bear rereading many times, and at any age. <br/><br/>Told from the first person perspective of the twelve-year-old Jewish girl, Patty Bergen, the story is rather bleak. As a Jewish girl living in a small Baptist American town, she already does not quite fit in. Furthermore, her parents favour her younger sister who is beautiful and talented, rejecti</span>
  <span id="freeText14653776227400839837" style="display:none">This was one of my favourite childhood books. Rereading it now for the first time as an adult, I am convinced this is one of those evergreen stories that will bear rereading many times, and at any age. <br /><br />Told from the first person perspective of the twelve-year-old Jewish girl, Patty Bergen, the story is rather bleak. As a Jewish girl living in a small Baptist American town, she already does not quite fit in. Furthermore, her parents favour her younger sister who is beautiful and talented, rejecting Patty’s awkward and over-the-top calls for attention. When Patty’s frequent attempts to engage her parents fail, she makes scenes, tells outrageous lies and makes snide remarks as a way of saving her dignity, which of course do nothing to further her cause with her parents. In this self-perpetuating cycle, she loses more and more of her parents’ regard for her as well as her own sense of self-worth. <br /><br />The plot thickens when the escaped German POW Anton Reiker comes into her life. She harbours him for the summer and he leaves when he realises what a risk his presence was putting her and her housekeeper at. Commentary on the novel has always stated how crucial this encounter with Anton is as he teaches her that she is a person of value. I’m divided though whether that fateful summer when she met (and lost) Anton was really such a good thing for her. Her love for words and sincere interest paid to the people she meets earn her the friendship of the reporter Charlene Madlee in much the same way that she earns that of Anton Reiker, and it seems to me likely that even without having met Anton, she would have found less controversial mentors outside of her family along the way. <br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[The price of meeting and falling in love with Anton is that she ends up in a reformatory home, and her thoughts of the future are filled with fantasies of escaping to Germany when she is eighteen, and finding acceptance and love with Anton's family, Anton himself having been shot dead in the course of his escape. Is the state she finds herself in at the end of the novel healthier than her previous situation of living a rather boring but relatively sheltered life with her neglectful and at times abusive family? <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />Regardless, the character of Patty was drawn in a most realistic way. Greene certainly has got the psychology of a twelve-year-old girl spot on. I love the way she falls into moods of jealousies and wishful thinking and how she picks herself up again after each fall. Her internal monologues are a joy to read, and so succinctly written that they don’t slow down the pace of the book at all.<br /><br />Many other themes are explored in the book, most notably the position of the black helper in a white household in the 1930’s. Other than Patty, the character of the housekeeper Ruth is the most rounded out. A mentor to Patty as well, her influence is however limited due to the colour of her skin.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14653776227400839837" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


