<div id="review_596714824" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/596714824" />
    <a title="Abra" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/15607836-abra"><img alt="Abra" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1357189304p2/15607836.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/596714824?book_show_action=true">Apr 21, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Abra" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Abra" href="/user/show/15607836-abra">Abra</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/15607836-abra?shelf=2013">2013</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/15607836-abra?shelf=re-read">re-read</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/15607836-abra?shelf=historical-yaf">historical-yaf</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer596714824" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4182151883723547468">This was one of my favorite books in middle school, and I&apos;ve re-read it several times since then. It speaks to anyone who has ever felt like an outcast. Patty Bergen&apos;s utter feeling of alienation from almost every single human in her general vicinity sounded a chord in me at that age, for sure. The alienation arises from many different circumstances, among which are her status as a Southern Jewish girl during WWII, and her love of words and reading. The only people she could feel close to at all</span>
  <span id="freeText4182151883723547468" style="display:none">This was one of my favorite books in middle school, and I've re-read it several times since then. It speaks to anyone who has ever felt like an outcast. Patty Bergen's utter feeling of alienation from almost every single human in her general vicinity sounded a chord in me at that age, for sure. The alienation arises from many different circumstances, among which are her status as a Southern Jewish girl during WWII, and her love of words and reading. The only people she could feel close to at all were her little sister (even though that was difficult since she felt her younger sister was favored over her, and certainly not the recipient of the emotional and physical abuse she received), their Black housekeeper, whom she loved deeply, a poor white boy whose friendship her father denied her... and the escaped German POW of the title. <br /><br />Re-reading this novel today, I saw that my ebook had a new forward which kind of blew me away. It's called "Bette Greene's Affadavit", and in it, the author acknowledges that this is a true story, and that she is Patty Bergen, and Patty Bergen is her. I never even IMAGINED that, as a child, reading the book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4182151883723547468" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review596714824">
  <td colspan="2">
